Part 2

The Punarjeevan shelter had no gate keeper.

The rusted iron gate sat half-open, held in place by an old brick to keep it from swinging in the dust from the bypass road.

Vikram had walked four kilometers before the first truck driver offered him a lift on a flatbed carrying concrete pipes.

He had sat on the wooden bench of the driver's cabin, the smell of grease and raw diesel filling his lungs, saying nothing until the driver let him off near the bypass.

Sarita was sitting in the front courtyard under the shade of a drumstick tree.

She had a large plastic tub of red chillies in her lap, sorting the split ones from the whole.

Her saree was faded cotton, the color of wet brick.

She didn't look up when the gate creaked.

"We don't have visitor hours on Friday," she said.

"I am not a visitor," Vikram said.

She stopped sorting the chillies.

She looked at his leather bag. Then at his dusty shoes.

"Rohan signed?" she asked.

"He signed."

"And you?"

"I signed first."

Sarita went back to the chillies. A dry, rustling sound as she moved them.

"This is not a guesthouse, Mr. Ahuja."

"I know."

"We don't have clean sheets. We don't have separate rooms. The men sleep in the side hall. Six on the floor. One on the wooden bench."

"I can sleep on the floor," Vikram said.

She stood up, keeping the plastic tub on the stone ledge of the well.

Her hands were slightly red from the chilli dust.

"You're thirty-five," she said, looking him in the eye. "Same as me. You've sat in a leather chair for ten years. You think this is a retreat. A peace-finding exercise."

"No," Vikram said.

"It isn't. The municipal corporation cuts our water line twice a month because we don't pay the grease money. The local school refuses our kids. And three times a year, someone dies in the back room and we have to argue with the police to let us bury them without a post-mortem."

She wiped her hands on her saree.

"I have the virus, Vikram. I've had it for six years. My husband gave it to me before he died. Most people in this house have it. You don't."

"I know," Vikram said.

"Then why are you standing at my gate with two shirts?"

"Because nobody here calls me Ahuja Sahib," Vikram said.

Sarita studied his face for a long moment.

The wind from the bypass brought the dry smell of burnt rubber from the tire repair shops.

"Go to the well," she said finally. "Wash the dust off. Ramu's nephew brings the tea at five. It is cheap tea. We don't have sugar today, only jaggery."

---

The well water was cold.

Vikram drew a bucket, the hemp rope rough against his palms.

He washed his face, his neck, the dust of the Nandyal roads and the study room sliding off his skin.

A girl was standing near the drumstick tree, watching him.

She was thin, wearing a oversized blue frock that had a tear near the hem.

Her hair was tied in two tight plates.

She looked fourteen, perhaps fifteen. Her collarbones stood out sharp under the thin fabric.

"You are the factory man," she said.

"My name is Vikram."

"Sarita didi said you own the big trucks."

"My brother owns them now," Vikram said.

She came closer. Her eyes were large, dark, and had the specific, unblinking curiosity of a child who had grown up around adults who had stopped hiding things from her.

"I am Ananya," she said.

"Do you go to school, Ananya?"

"The school closed for me," she said, without sadness. "They said my blood is bad."

"Who said that?"

"The headmaster. He told Sarita didi that if I sit near the other girls, their parents will stop paying the fee. Sarita didi argued. She has a loud voice when she's angry. But the gate remained locked."

She looked at his leather bag near the well.

"What is inside?"

"Two shirts," Vikram said.

"No toys?"

"No."

"I have a wooden horse," she said proudly. "Ramu's nephew made it. It has only three legs, but it stands if you lean it against the wall."

Vikram smiled.

The first real smile since the doctor's phone call at four in the morning.

"Show me," he said.

---

They sat on the low stone wall of the well.

The wooden horse was small, carved from a branch of the drumstick tree.

Ananya leaned it against the bucket.

It stood.

"See?" she said. "It doesn't need the fourth leg. It is just for show."

Sarita came out carrying a steel kettle and three mismatched glasses.

She set them on the stone ledge.

The tea was dark red. No milk. The jaggery had turned it the color of boiled tamarind.

"Drink," she said.

Vikram held the glass.

The heat of the glass was direct, burning his fingers slightly.

He took a sip.

The jaggery was sweet, but the tea was strong, bitter at the edges.

Outside, the bypass traffic went on.

The trucks honked. The dust rose.

But inside the courtyard, the red tea tasted of nothing but the well water and the shade of the drumstick tree.

"It is good," Vikram said.

Sarita sat on the well wall beside Ananya.

She put her arm around the girl's shoulder, pulling her close.

"It is cheap," Sarita said. "But it is ours."

Vikram drank.

He looked at the three-legged horse, at Ananya's laughter as she knocked it down and set it up again, at Sarita's quiet face.

The fourteen hundred crore had gone to Nandyal.

The office keys were on the teak wood desk.

But the red tea in his glass smelled better than any tea he had ever had in a boardroom.

[End of Part 2]
